				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$$BVSE(M)=\frac{{D}_{0}}{2}\left\{{\left(\exp \left[\alpha \left({R}_{\min }-R\right)\right]-1\right)}^{2}-1\right\}+\mathop{\sum }\limits_{i=1}^{N}{E}_{{\rm{Coulomb}}}(M-{M}_{i}).$$\end{document}BVSE(M)=D02expαRmin−R−12−1+ ∑i=1NECoulomb(M−Mi).

The Morse-type potential is characterized by the empirical BV parameters: D0, α, and Rmin48,49. The use of D0/2 as the Morse bond breaking energy prevents double-counting of the same interaction in both the energy landscapes of M and Mi and may be seen as taking into account in a simplified average way relaxations in the immobile substructure, as the suppression of relaxations in the static BVSE modelling tends to overestimate the migration barriers. The Coulomb repulsions between two different cations (or between anions) M1 and M2 is calculated by the following formula:2\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
